item.title: A Puckett Proposal
item.description:
Hi everyone, Im MrPuckett In 24 hours I'm going to ask the woman I love to marry me.
If you've seen my posts you might know that I moved to Minnesota almost 2 years ago and fell in love In June my 2 dogs and I moved in with her and her 4 dogs
It's a lot of shelter and rescue dogs but hey, we could probably fit a few more in there
When we first met I think I tried really hard not to fall for her. It had been 10 years since I was in a relationship and I thought I loved being alone more than anything
But then she was the kindest, most compassionate and caring person I had ever met Every step we took together came so easily, every big decision brought us closer together.
On Monday I snuck out of our place and went to her parents house. I told them "I wanted to start planning Lindsey's birthday"
But I was actually there to ask her parent's permission to marry their daughter. They're amazing people and accepted me as family long before this. Tears were shed, hugs were had, permission was granted.
Now it's time to actually plan the proposal.
She and I had talked about this a lot before. I said I wanted a big crazy proposal like - Halftime of a football game on the jumbotron or go to a zoo and ask them to hang a banner from a giraffe's neck with the proposal or something But she always envisioned it being more simple than that.
So I schemed up this whole morning Saturday where I'll get down on one knee in her parent's backyard surrounded by family and 6 dogs as our song plays - Can't Help Falling In Love With You by Elvis. And I'll ask her to spend the rest of our lives together.
Im excited to be Kevin's dad.
For 10 years I thought I wanted to spend the rest of my life alone And on our 2nd date, as she watched squirrels out the window because my dog wanted to, I couldn't help but think
This is the one.
So while tomorrow will bring a lot of nerves and probably a few fumbled words
There isn't a doubt in my mind. I'm madly in love with her and I can't wait to ask her to marry me.

item.title: I’m sorry, body. ❤️
item.description:
For years I have warred with myself over my body - its appearance, its limitations. Self-consciousness in spades from purity culture, postpartum changes, weight gain, and the general society in which we live.
For over 15 years I have been TERRIFIED for people to see my belly in particular - all the stretch marks, loose skin, surgical scars. I used to have literal nightmares about people seeing my stomach. That shit runs deep.
I was coming back from Italy recently and I saw a woman at the airport in a crop top, stretch marks like mine. And you know what? She was BEAUTIFUL. There was no shame in how she carried herself, only power. I’ve thought about her a lot since.
I’m grateful for my body. I’m down more than 65 lbs as I continuously work to improve my health. But this body allows me to cuddle puppies and travel the world and hug my loved ones.
So I’m sorry, body, that I have ever been ashamed. That I’ve ever hidden you away. I can’t promise to never feel that way again, but this post? Showing friends and strangers alike what I look like? This is something I would have never in a million years thought myself capable of. ❤️❤️

item.title: Rest in Peace, Debbie
item.description: To start off, I'm not related to any of them. They didn't have to trust me and give me a place to live/then rent when I found work, which was thankfully quickly. I don't know what's going to happen with the place she leased, and me... her now widowed husband... her sister and two of their grandkids live. We have til April on the lease but not sure how to make the money difference lost by her. We miss her a lot... and it's crazy I'm typing this today... the day it happened but I needed to get it out. I'm gonna try to help them keep this place like she would've wanted for everyone. I feel like it's the least I can do to try to pay respects. It's crazy, I just talked to her yesterday. About some mundane stuff. (Toilet paper, tbh. Gave her 10$ to get some) I can't believe she's gone. Anyways... always appreciate the time you get with people. And try not to fight too often. We bashed heads occasionally with noise etc, but I always had a home here, which has been rare in my life. Much love to you all. Give some hugs out to those you care about today. You never know. Thank you Debbie. Rest easy okay
